buildConfig: 
the whole purpose of having build config is to automate the process of building container images from either source code or another image
1. create a buildConfig by adding a yaml file in OpenShift
2. run $ oc new-app <app-link-in-github> in terminal
it would show that buildconfig.build.openshift.io "blabla" created in the output, that's how to create a build config manually
actually when create an application, a build config will be auto-created

then start a build in terminal:
$ oc start-build <build-config-name>
alternatively start a build in OpenShift UI:
click the build config, select 'start build' in the ellipsis, after it's finished, the created image can be found in 'output to' in Details


Build configuration stratefy:
there are 4 strategies to create the build configuration:
1. S2I (source to image): a tool to create a docker-formatted container image, then injects source code into it
2. pipeline: defined in Jenkinsfile, and manged via OpenShift
3. docker/buildah build
4. custom: define a custom builder image which is a plain docker-formatted container image embedded with build process logic

Build input:
git -> dockerfile -> binary -> image -> input secrets -> external artifacts (not recommanded)

1. S2I: https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/openshift_container_platform/3.11/html/using_images/source-to-image-s2i
it takes code and creates a docker-compliant container image, then push that image to a docker registry.
benefits: dev dont need to create a docker file; it's more secure since dev can create permissions, authentication, authorisation to decide who can create that container image.

2. buildah: a tool that builds container images

3. S2I vs custom build:
S2I:
Git Repository
       │
       ▼
OpenShift Official Builder Image
(Java, Node.js, Python, etc.)
       │
       ▼
Compile the source code
       │
       ▼
Generate a Container Image

custom build:
Git Repository
       │
       ▼
Your own Custom Builder Image
       │
       ├── Download dependencies
       ├── Execute custom scripts
       ├── Compile the application
       ├── Package the application
       ├── Run tests
       └── Generate the final container image


build triigers:
to avoid manually start a build in OpenShift, there are 3 types of build triggers:
1. Webhooks: github, gitlab, bitbucket etc. as soon as code gets updated, it auto-triggers the build in OpenShift
2. ImageChange: the image stream tag change creates an automatic build, not recommanded for dev environment, staging environment is fine
3. ConfigChange
these values can be setup in BuildConfigs -> YAML -> triggers.type, and can be seen in Builds -> TriggeredBy or YAML
